(332, 1, '2016-05-24 07:43:29', '2016-05-24 07:43:29', 'It all started when a bunch of visionaries saw an opportunity for such an event in a dynamic community. The co-operation and support of many local business and the cooperation of the Emerald Agricultural College, saw the location of the grounds at the Agricultural College, laser levelled and prepared, streets and lanes constructed, and basic water and power infrastructures installed in record time. Toilets at the time, I think were basic but indicative of things to come. Now the facilities are amongst the best in Australia and the crowds are catered for more comfortably.\r\n\r\nThe first year saw 90 exhibitors and it has grown from there. The record year was 2007 with 567 exhibitors and over one thousand five hundred traders. This was definitely bolstered by the mining community which almost doubled the numbers overnight. The mining industry is fickle however, and numbers have reduced to about 350 to 400 exhibitors and around 1200 traders all basically servicing the stable Farming communities. Our formula of having trading done by both producers and suppliers has proven successful as it is basically getting the two groups together at the one time.\r\n\r\nStud Bull sales are complimented by Stock horse sales and cattle dog trials and sales. Last year we introduced the Colt Starting competition which has proved extremely popular and it will become a fixture I believe. We compliment that with some areas for socialising, to catch up and enjoy the environment with someone you may well have not seen for the past 12 months. The township of Emerald responds with social get togethers and activities outside the core event which complement the event so well.\r\n\r\nNever before has the reliance on the Farming industry been so obvious, since the decline of the Mining Industry. The Resources Industry it seems has had the Politicians giddy with the balance of trade figures to such an extent that they took their eyes off the ball. Aside from the reckless spending, Farming has been placed at the bottom of the list in priorities of National Importance. I believe the Farming Industry should be regarded as a National Security item and should receive all of the favours reserved for the National Defence (Army Navy Air Force) including a slice of the National Defence budget.\r\n\r\nIts only a spend of that magnitude that is going to get us in step with the infrastructures needed to supply the exponential demands for food and fibre. Our tropical water for example is a massive waste of potential irrigation supply. Asia is on our doorstep and the demands are real. Free trade agreements will only put us on the short list for even more product. If everyone in China alone developed a taste for our quality products, we would be swamped.\r\n\r\nI believe we must catch up and prepare for the exponential growths coming from that country alone. I spend a couple of months in China every year and Im amazed at their demand for our Baby formula and WAs wheat products alone. A burgeoning middle class will only see those demands increase beyond our abilities to produce. Price is not their resistance, its quality assurance, and we have the highest in the world.\r\n\r\nA dry spell we might well have had, but as we all know, the seasons change and the task ahead is enormous.\r\n\r\nAg-Grow is pleased to play our part in bringing increased efficiencies to the farming community and welcome the new exhibitors to our field days. Your trading is not confined to three days, but a relationship builder for years to come. Its about filling your tally book with contacts and potential sales.\r\n\r\nIts about the long haul. One hit wonders do put a toe in the water but those with long term commitments to the bush are seen here year after year and to those who have this long term commitment, I especially welcome, as many of you have done the 25 year journey and are well positioned to harvest into the future.\r\n\r\nI trust everyone enjoys the genuine opportunities afforded at Westpac Ag-Grow in its 25th year of servicing the township of Emerald and the greater Central and Northern Queensland.\r\n\r\n<strong>Managing Director</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Geoff Dein</strong>', 'Managing Director''s Welcome', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-05-24 07:43:29', '2016-05-24 07:43:29', '', 9, 'http://aggrow.stagingdevsite.com/dev/9-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
